{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528058"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14260"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14260"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.15,0.02,0.35,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6955"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"10886"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12084"},{"type":"tags","id":"12765"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic for management advice following a recent diagnosis of hepatitis B. She was tested as part of a community screening programme and has received counselling, education and support around the diagnosis. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She reports feeling well and denies any symptoms. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no signs of chronic liver disease. Recent investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg): Positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis B e antigen (HBeAg): Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis B viral DNA: 10,000 IU/mL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 35 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 30 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 40 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 15 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 1.0 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransient elastography: 4 kPa (2-7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Six-monthly liver function tests","Six-monthly liver ultrasound","Six-monthly transient elastography","Commence tenofovir","Six-monthly viral load monitoring"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 38-year-old Aboriginal woman recently diagnosed with chronic hepatitis B. This patient has HBeAg-negative chronic hepatitis B with normal ALT and a viral load below 20,000 IU/mL, which does not meet criteria for antiviral therapy. However, regular monitoring enables the assessment of disease activity and helps determine when treatment may become necessary. According to ASHM guidelines, the patient requires \u003Cstrong\u003Esix-monthly monitoring of liver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E and annual \u003Cstrong\u003Emonitoring of viral load, rather than six-monthly.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix-monthly liver ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) surveillance is recommended for certain high-risk groups with chronic hepatitis B. According to ASHM guidelines, these include Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people from age 50, Asian males from age 40, Asian females from age 50, people from sub-Saharan Africa over 20, people with cirrhosis, and those with a family history of HCC. Additionally, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people aged 40 years or older with high-risk genotypes should commence six-monthly ultrasound surveillance. This patient is 38 years old, so six-monthly ultrasounds are not yet indicated, but should commence when she reaches 50 (or 40 if she has a high-risk genotype).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix-monthly transient elastography\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this stage. While transient elastography is a useful non-invasive tool for assessing liver fibrosis, annual assessment is sufficient in stable patients with chronic hepatitis B who are not on treatment. The current result shows no significant fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing tenofovir\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. According to ASHM guidelines, antiviral therapy is typically recommended for patients with chronic hepatitis B who have: cirrhosis (regardless of ALT or viral load), significant fibrosis (F2 or greater) with viral load \u0026gt;2,000 IU/mL and elevated ALT, HBeAg-positive disease with viral load \u0026gt;20,000 IU/mL and ALT \u0026gt;2x upper limit of normal, or HBeAg-negative disease with viral load \u0026gt;2,000 IU/mL and ALT \u0026gt;2x upper limit of normal. This patient does not meet these criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix-monthly viral load monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is more frequent than necessary. In stable patients with chronic hepatitis B who are not on treatment, annual viral load monitoring is typically sufficient, alongside six-monthly liver function tests. In Australia, hepatitis B DNA testing is subsidised through Medicare annually for patients not receiving treatment and up to four times per year for those on antiviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to monitoring, management should include screening and vaccination of household contacts and sexual partners. Education about the disease, its transmission, and the importance of regular follow-up is critical. It is important that care is culturally safe, with careful consideration of language, communication and worldviews. There are hepatitis B resources specifically designed for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, which can be offered if not already provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic hepatitis B patients with normal liver function and low viral loads require regular monitoring with six-monthly liver function tests.","Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people with chronic hepatitis B should undergo hepatocellular carcinoma surveillance with six-monthly ultrasound from 50 years of age, or from 40 years if they have a high-risk genotype.","Antiviral therapy for chronic hepatitis B is indicated when specific thresholds for viral load, ALT elevation, or fibrosis are met."],"references":["Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine. Management and care of hepatitis B. Sydney: ASHM; 2022. Available at: https://ashm.org.au/hepatitis-b-toolkit/management-and-care-of-hepatitis-b","Lubel, J.S., Strasser, S.I., Thompson, A.J., Cowie, B.C., MacLachlan, J., Allard, N.L., Holmes, J., Kemp, W.W., Majumdar, A., Iser, D., Howell, J. and Matthews, G.V. (2022), Australian consensus recommendations for the management of hepatitis B. Med J Aust, 216: 478-486. https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.51430","Hepatitis B toolkit: caring for Aboriginal Victorians. Available at: https://ashm.org.au/hepatitis-b-toolkit/caring-for-aboriginal-victorians/","Menzies School of Health Research. Hep B Story App. 2014. Available at: https://www.menzies.edu.au/page/Resources/Hep_B_Story/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14260"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T21:05:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T21:05:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6955"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Manage